Finally, in two passages (c. 25 18 31 31) A has fortunately retained the compendium, falsely resolved in all other MSS„ which enables us to restore the original. In general, it may be said that the corruptions, barring one or two exceptions, are not of a very serious nature, being often due to the scribe’s inability to interpret correctly the abbreviations with which the archetypon, as we shall see, must have abounded. The curious mutilation of well-known proper names also shows him to have been a man of little learning. And in spite of his assurance ‘meliusculum feci ' he resorted to conjectures but rarely, and these are, strictly speaking, rather in the nature of unimportant changes than of intentional emendation.
